  "text": "N umerous clinical studies have indicated that diabetic patients have a higher incidence of restenosis after percutaneous coronary interventions compared with patients without diabetes. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Excellent results have been achieved with drug-eluting stents, with significant reductions in restenosis rates. However, drug-eluting stents themselves delay reendothelialization, and diabetic patients continue to have excessive rates of restenosis, including thrombosis that may cause acute coronary syndrome.",
